			<h4><a name="16786795">24 bit?</a></h4>


		 	<span id="comment_score_16786795" class="score">(Score:5, Insightful)</span>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			by <a href="//slashdot.org/~voidptr">voidptr (609)</a> 
			<span class="otherdetails">
				
				on Thursday November 09, @11:40AM (<a href="//slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=205731&amp;cid=16786795">#16786795</a>)
				<small><br>(<a href="http://www.csh.rit.edu/~sunday">http://www.csh.rit.edu/~sunday</a> | Last Journal: <a href="//slashdot.org/~voidptr/journal/">Saturday October 21, @02:17PM</a>) </small>
			</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">	
		<div id="comment_body_16786795">Why on earth does MySQL have a 24 bit integer datatype? On what platform does it even remotely make sense to use that in the first place? It's going to get cast to 32 bits for any arithmetic operations anyway, and on most platforms today alignment requirements are going to pad the extra byte in memory and disk, so you're not even saving any space. Why even give someone the option over choosing between 16 bit and 32 bit integers?</div>
	</div>

